***REMOVED*** Phosphoproteomic Analysis

Brett Engelmann(Integrative Proteomics)

February 7th, 2019

Overview

T cells derived from ***REMOVED*** kinase dead (D137N mutation within HRD motif) and wild type mice were ex vivo stiumlated with H_2O_2 or CD3/CD28 at specific time points. The goal of this project is to assess changes in phosphoproteomic profiles due to treatment and/or strain.

Note that a time dependent phenotypic change in cell adhesion was observed.

The data were processed with maxquant/andromeda (V 1.6.0.16) on 1/14/19 using the mouse database Mus_musculus.GRCm38.95.pep.all.parsedCCDS.fa retrieved from Ensembl on the same day.32956 translated transcripts with CCDS identifiers are present in this FASTA file. A common contaminants list was appended to this FASTA to facilitate their exclusion. The mq parameters file mqpar1_14_19 in this directory has all the MQ parameter choices.

Some key MaxQuant processing parameters:

  • FixedMod = Carbamidomethyl
  • VarMod = Oxidation(M); Acetyl (Protein N-term); Phospho (STY) (for appropriate samples)
  • PSM/Protein/Site FDR = .01 using reverted database as decoys
  • The match-between-runs (MBR) feature was enabled
  • Label free quantification (MQ-LFQ) on XICs was employed

Below I analyze the data from the project. Specifically, I assess coverage and quality, transform and normalize the data, perform EDA, impute, and batch effect correct the data. Then, I construct the proper statistical models for differential phosphorylation analysis. Then, I perform a series of enrichment analyses on the data using appropriate ontologies. Finally, the results are exported in a format suitable for web-application deployment.

Phosphoproteome Coverage

80.3% of the identified peptides were phosphorylated.

Mass error by intensity, AA breakdown, and phosphopeptide multiplicity (phosphopeptide phosphorylation count) pie and venn diagram overlay by site (AA position within the protein).

Average mass error is 0.0389473 parts per milllion. There is no strong relationship between intensity and mass error.

Breakdown of phosphosites by AA and multiplicity is as expected

Most phosphosites are observed as singletons.

Identification and quantification

MQ outputs a Phospho (STY)Sites summary table that gives all sites within a protein that are identified. Singly, doubly, and triply phosphorylated peptides that map/localize to this site are quantified. Class 1 sites are sites with median localiztion probability ~.95 and minimum localization probability of .75.

12483 sites were identified in at least one sample at an FDR of 1%. A breakdown of phoshposites by identification, quantification, and localization probability:

Model Definitions

We would like to identify differentially phosphorylated peptides between or across: 1) Strains 2) Treatments 3) Times

All models are wrong but some are useful - George Box

Model 1 only includes zeros and treatments at time 5 min to test for differential phosphorylation across strains and treatments. This model will include an interaction effect whose coefficients will test for treatment specific strain differences at a single time point (5 or 0 minutes).

Model 2 is a generalized additive model (GAM) that uses data normalized to strain specific 0s will be used to test for differences at any point in time within and across each strain in response to CD3/CD28 costimultaion. The first model, although it does not use all the data, benefits from the other data at the normalization and imputation steps. The second model, although it loses degrees of freedom by standardizing to zero removes the issue of confounding between time 0 and untreated. Separate heuristics will be applied to each model in order to ensure all suitable data is applied.

Model I - Differences Due to Treatment and/or Strain

Linear regression model with surrogate variables (see below) added as covariates:

\[Y_{ijk} = Treat_i + Strain_j + Treat_i*Strain_j + SV_l + {\epsilon}_{ijk}: i = none,CD3/CD28,H_2O_2; j=WT,Mutant; k = 1,...,16; l=1,...,N\] where \(Y_{ijk}\) is logged phosphosite intensity of culture replicate k from strain j treatment i. \(Treat_i\) is the estimated effect from treatment i, \(Strain_j\) is the estimated effect from strain j and the interaction term is the estimated effect of treatment specific strain effects. \(SV_k\) is the estimated effect from a covariate surrogate variable l identified from the data.

Heuristic I

For model I a phosphopeptide needs to be observed in either:

  1. at least half of the biological replicates for each treatment (for more confident imputation: an anchor in every treatment)
  2. all of the biological replicates for any single treatment (for new phosphopeptides unique to a single treatment)
  3. at least half of the biological replicates for each strain (for more confident imputation: an anchor in every strain)
  4. all of the biological replicates for any single strain (for new phosphopeptides unique to a single strain)

4163 phosphopeptides satisfy any of the above conditions. The ts.frame.passed and ts.frame.binary.passed data frames are used for modeling. The binary data frame has the logical results of the heuristic test associated with each peptide. The peptides that do not pass the test have been removed.

Model II - Differences Due to Treatment

For each strain a time zero estimate is calculated. The data are normalized to the strain specific zero time point. A generalized additive model is fit with a natural cubic spline smoothing function which captures nonlinear temporal phosphosite profiles. More specifically,

\[Y_{ijk} = Strain_j + Strain_j*S(Time_k) + {\epsilon}_{ijk}: i = 1,...,12; j=WT,***REMOVED***; k=5,20,60\]

where \(Y_{ijk}\) is logged phosphosite intensity of culture replicate i from strain j at time k. \(Strain_j\) is the estimated average effect from strain j, \(S(Time_k)\) is a smoothing function that will capture effects of time on phosphopeptide intensity levels. The smoothing function used is a natural cubic spline, that is the second derivative = 0 at the boundary knots. A single knot is automatically chosen at the 50th quantile of the data (20 min here). boundary knots are at 0 and 60 min. The interaction term is the estimated effect of strain specific timecourse profiles.

Heuristic II

Due to sample processing issues, a few donors have missing samples. For the timecourse, a phosphopeptide is considered if it has either:

  1. at least 3 observations in each strain (half of the samples for each strain)
  2. all times (not samples) observed in either strain

1 ensures that we are using imputation results grounded by real measurements and 2 ensures we are not throwing away sites that turn on/off in specific strains (largest postentially most significant findings)

3256 phosphopeptides satisfy either 1 or 2 from heuristic II. The MedianQuantiledImputedCentered.passed and MedianQuantiledImputedCentered.binary.passed data frames are used for modeling. The binary data frame has the logical results of the heuristic II test associated with each peptide. The peptides that do not pass the test have been removed.

Latent variation correction with SVA

Here I attempt to correct for unwanted latent sources of variation with surrogate variable analysis (SVA), a popular form of weighted factor analysis. For the first model I have protected treatment and strain and for the second model I have protected the effects of time and strain using a generalized additive model (see section above for more details on each model).

Inference

Differential phosphorylation is performed with the limma framework for both models.

Model I

4163 phosphopeptides were ultimately fit to the interaction model (see Model Definitions above). The three SVs identified above were included as covariates.

## [1] TRUE

A few EDA plots show no obvious artifacts associated with this analysis.

Example plot

Below is the peptide with the lowest p-value testing the null hypothesis that there is no difference in phosphosite levels between CD3.CD28.wt samples and CD3.CD28.mut samples. Here idmult = 6173_1 is used with the SV.regressed.modelI and ts.frame.binary.passed data frames. Two different faceting approaches are applied.

Model II

A natural cubic spline was fit to each CD3/CD28 stimulated timecourse. I used the SV regressed data frame containing 3256 phosphopeptides that passed the heuristics for model II outlined above.

Three types of tests were performed:

  1. Differential phosphorylation across strains at any time
  2. A significant change in phosphorylation due to time
  3. A change in the time effect across strains (interaction)

Spline plot examples

The top hit idmult 7072_2 for within-strain mutant time effect is plotted below. Here I used with the SV.regressed.modelII and meta.data.centered data frames.

Enrichment Analysis

Enrichments on PhosphoSitePlus kinase substrate information as well as reactome and go (bp,mf,cc, slim). Each annotation is represented at least three times in the dataset to be considered.

Data Export

Exported:

  1. The median, quantile normalized, imputed (across all samples) and SV regressed, phosphopeptide XICs for models I and II
  2. The MS meta data and other identifiers associated with each site
  3. A binary matrix indicating if a data point was measured (1) or imputed (0) for models I and II
  4. Study meta data
  5. Results from inferences tests from models I and II
  6. Results of all enrichment analyses

Numbers 1 and 2 are combined into a single table SiteTableCombined. Note that the SiteTableCombined table has a dupidmult column for duplicated quantifications that account for doubly or triply phosphorylated peptides mapping to mulitple sites. Numbers 3 and 4 are single tables. 4 may or may not be available.

note that multiply phosphorylated peptides are only represented once and therefore in such cases the site of modification is not unique

The key for annotation mergining is the ENSMUSP identifier in the protein column. MGI symbols that map to protein ENSMUSPs are sourced from biomart ensembl94 database. note that some proteins do not have MGI symbols mapped
